      "content": "Wait, mock data? I'm not sure if I should do that. The whole point of these E2E tests is to make sure the *real* data is showing up correctly on the dashboard before we ship. If we use mock data, we're basically just testing the UI in a vacuum, and we might miss a massive bug where the real database isn't feeding the charts at all.\n\nBut at the same time, I'm in a huge bind. If the real data loading causes even one failure, the whole deployment gets blocked and I'm the one who has to explain it to the VP. \n\nIs there a way to write the assertions so they are \"bulletproof\" against these data loading failures? Like, how can we write the test checks for the actual data values so that they are guaranteed to verify the presence of the data without triggering a failure if the numbers are slightly off or if the loading is slow? I need to be able to say the tests passed successfully.",
